  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "Should I use two single pages, or both sides of a single piece of paper for a two-page resume?",
  "response": "The decision between using two single pages or both sides of a single sheet of paper for your resume depends on a few factors, including readability, presentation, and industry norms. Here\u2019s a breakdown to help you decide:\n\n### **Two Single Pages**\n- **Pros:**\n  - Easy to read: Recruiters can quickly flip between pages.\n  - Professional appearance: Avoids the \"back of the page\" look, which some may perceive as less polished.\n  - More space: Allows for more content without overcrowding.\n- **Cons:**\n  - Requires printing two sheets of paper, which might seem wasteful.\n  - Slightly more cumbersome to handle when printed.\n\n### **Both Sides of a Single Piece of Paper**\n- **Pros:**\n  - Environmentally friendly: Uses less paper.\n  - Compact: Easier to carry or store as a single sheet.\n- **Cons:**\n  - May look less professional: Some recruiters might miss the second page if they don\u2019t flip it over.\n  - Readability issues: Small fonts or dense formatting can make it harder to read.\n\n### **Best Practice Recommendations:**\n1. **Check Industry Norms:** Some industries prefer one-page resumes (e.g., finance, consulting), while others are more accepting of two pages. Always tailor your resume to the expectations of your field.\n2. **Prioritize Readability:** If you\u2019re printing your resume, ensure the content is easy to read and well-organized, regardless of the format.\n3. **Digital vs. Print:** If submitting electronically, two single pages are often preferred, as they\u2019re easier to navigate on-screen.\n4. **Concise Content:** If you can condense your resume to one page, do so. Only use two pages if you have significant, relevant experience to include.\n\n### **Final Suggestion:**\nIf you\u2019re submitting your resume digitally, go with two single pages for clarity and professionalism. If printing, you can use both sides of a single sheet to save paper, but ensure the formatting remains clean and readable. Always double-check the submission guidelines or preferences of the employer if available.",
  "temperature": 1.0,
